Here is a silly=C2=A0but not entirely inaccurate description of the nickel =
market right now:=09Nickel is worth, let=E2=80=99s say, somewhere between $=
30,000 and $35,000 per ton.=09Everyone kind of knows that.=09For reasons of=
 historical accident and market technicals, the price of nickel on the Lond=
on Metal Exchange, the main venue for nickel trading, was set at $48,078 pe=
r ton at the start of trading yesterday morning, about 40% above the real p=
rice.=09The LME declared that the price could drop by only 5% per day (sinc=
e expanded to 8% per day) until it reached the real price.=09So that=E2=80=
=99s happening now: It fell 5% yesterday, fell 8% today, will fall 8% tomor=
row, etc., until it hits the real price sometime around next Tuesday.=09The=
 price is preordained so there is not much to do: Each day the LME opens fo=
r trading, promptly falls 8% to reach the limit,=C2=A0and then closes again=
.=09Nor is there much volume because, you know, if the real price of nickel=
 is $35,000, why are you paying $42,000?=09But there=E2=80=99s some volume,=
 and the only real question is who gets to the front of the line to sell ni=
ckel at today=E2=80=99s inflated price before the market shuts and you have=
 to wait until tomorrow for it to fall some more.I mean? I am kidding? But =
only a little? It is not=C2=A0really=C2=A0the case that nickel is definitel=
y worth $30,000 to $35,000 a ton, or that everyone knows that, or that the =
price will automatically keep dropping 8% a day. (This is not investment ad=
vice!) But it kind of looks like that? It is not a great look?Let me explai=
n a bit more.=C2=A0At the beginning of March, nickel was trading at about $=
25,000 a ton. Since then nickel has become more valuable as Russia=E2=80=99=
s invasion of Ukraine has put pressure on nickel supplies. The fundamental =
value has gone up, to perhaps $30,000 or $35,000 a ton, somewhere=C2=A0in t=
hat ballpark, the exact number doesn=E2=80=99t matter.[1] However, due to a=
 short squeeze on the London Metal Exchange, nickel futures shot up last we=
ek, and the price  climbed above $100,000 per ton early in the morning of T=
uesday, March 8.=C2=A0In general the point of a futures market is to discov=
er the correct price for a commodity. But in the case of LME nickel last we=
ek, everyone =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, at least, everyone running the LME =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0sort of looked around and said =E2=80=9Cwell this is not the corre=
ct price of nickel now is it.=E2=80=9D (The chief executive officer of the =
LME said that=C2=A0the trading prices =E2=80=9Cwere becoming disconnected f=
rom, I believe, physical reality.=E2=80=9D) The LME, and many big metals tr=
aders, decided that the correct price of nickel was not $100,000. So the LM=
E canceled last Tuesday=E2=80=99s trades =E2=80=94=C2=A0a drastic step that=
 took away the profits and losses many traders had made on nickel that morn=
ing =E2=80=94=C2=A0and rolled the price back to $48,078, where nickel had c=
losed last Monday.Then the LME closed for a week to give people time to res=
olve the weird short-squeeze dynamics that had driven up the price. In part=
icular, there is one big nickel producer, Tsingshan Holding Group Co., run =
by nickel tycoon Xiang Guangda, that was short a lot=C2=A0of nickel contrac=
ts on the LME and got big margin calls last week and did not put up more mo=
ney. Some of its brokers bought back nickel contracts rather than posting m=
ore margin, which drove the price up more, which led to more margin calls, =
more forced selling, etc. Because all of this was somewhat silly =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0Tsingshan is probably good for the money, since it is a nickel produc=
er and the price of nickel is going up! =E2=80=94=C2=A0the way to fix it wa=
s to shut down the market for a while to let Tsingshan and others borrow en=
ough money (against their valuable nickel) to pay margin calls without havi=
ng to buy back their futures contracts. And that=E2=80=99s what happened, a=
nd they lined up financing, and when the market reopened yesterday the shor=
t squeeze was greatly alleviated. Nobody was forced to buy nickel at prices=
 that they thought were absurd, so they were all free to buy or sell nickel=
 at the correct price.Except, uh, no they weren=E2=80=99t, because the LME =
imposed price limits: The price of nickel could only rise or fall 5% yester=
day, from last Monday=E2=80=99s closing price of $48,078, when the short sq=
ueeze had already started and =E2=80=9C the market had started to unravel.=
=E2=80=9D It was not=C2=A0completely=C2=A0certain that the price would fall=
 5% =E2=80=94=C2=A0when Bloomberg  surveyed 16 analysts and traders before =
the reopening, 13 said that it would fall 5%, but one said it would rise 5%=
, =E2=80=9Cwhile the other two said either scenario is possible=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it was the most obvious outcome. Everyone seemed to thin=
k that the prices last week =E2=80=9Cwere becoming disconnected from physic=
al reality,=E2=80=9D and the LME had done the necessary things to get the p=
rice back in line with physical reality, so it stood to reason that the pri=
ce would fall back to physical reality. But because the LME put the brakes =
on how fast it could fall =E2=80=94=C2=A0from last week=E2=80=99s unreal pr=
ice! =E2=80=94=C2=A0it couldn=E2=80=99t do that all at once.And so the pric=
e immediately fell 5% yesterday, on very light volume (why sell at the wron=
g price?), and closed at $45,590.[2] To speed things along a little bit, th=
e LME then announced that=C2=A0today=C2=A0the price can fall (or rise?) by =
up to 8%. So it opened today, fell 8% to $41,945, and promptly stopped trad=
ing.=C2=A0I mean, that is a rough intuitive description of what happened to=
day;  here=E2=80=99s what actually happened:The start of the second day of =
trading after a week-long suspension was delayed to 8:45 a.m. after a serie=
s of problems hit the LME=E2=80=99s electronic system. First, brokers found=
 that orders to sell at the lower-limit of 8% below Wednesday=E2=80=99s clo=
sing price were being rejected, after the LME expanded the trading band the=
 previous day.Then three trades did appear to go through at that price -- b=
ut four minutes before the market had been due to open. Finally, the LME in=
formed brokers that trading wouldn=E2=80=99t restart until 8:45 a.m. and ca=
nceled the three earlier trades. When the market finally opened, futures dr=
opped by the daily limit of 8% to $41,945 a ton. But only two trades had ta=
ken place by 9:00 a.m.The chaotic start to the session piles embarrassment =
on the LME as it seeks to restore order to the market that sets global pric=
es for one of the world=E2=80=99s most important metals. The crisis in nick=
el has sparked furious criticism of the exchange for its handling of the si=
tuation, from metals markets veterans as well as generalist investors, and =
several have said they will stop trading on the market.=E2=80=9CCredibility=
 is very quickly slipping through their fingers,=E2=80=9D Keith Wildie, hea=
d of trading at Romco Metals, said by phone from London. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=
=99s eroding very rapidly.=E2=80=9DGood times, good times.Meanwhile, as we =
 discussed yesterday, the LME has suspended reporting an =E2=80=9COfficial =
Price=E2=80=9D while it does this weird slow walk back to the correct price=
. I suppose part of the rationale for this is that, since the limit-down pr=
ices reported on the LME this week are in some obvious sense not =E2=80=9Cc=
orrect,=E2=80=9D it would be strange to report them as official prices. But=
 the LME=E2=80=99s stated rationale, which is also a good one, is that =E2=
=80=9Cphysical users preferred not to have Official Prices which they had b=
een unable to trade=E2=80=9D: Because the limit-down prices this week are s=
ort of obviously too high, nobody really wants to buy at those prices, whic=
h means that almost nobody is able to sell at those prices, which means tha=
t if you want to trade nickel at those prices you mostly can=E2=80=99t. The=
 LME opens briefly to perform the mechanics of falling 8%, and then it clos=
es again; it won=E2=80=99t function as a real exchange until it gets all th=
e way back to the real price.I want to emphasize that I am being too cute h=
ere, pretending that the =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D price is knowable, and know=
n to be about $30,000 to $35,000. I don=E2=80=99t know the real price! In g=
eneral it is the job of markets to figure out the correct price! In the med=
ium term they are generally pretty good at that, but if you run a financial=
 futures market yes, sure, there will sometimes be weird technical dynamics=
 that affect the price from minute to minute, and it will occasionally=C2=
=A0be plausible to say stuff like =E2=80=9Cthe prices are becoming disconne=
cted from physical reality.=E2=80=9DIf you run an exchange and you think th=
at, one thing you could do would be to just say it and do nothing else. =E2=
=80=9CHey these prices are pretty weird,=E2=80=9D you might say on televisi=
on, and hopefully people will hear you and rethink what they=E2=80=99re doi=
ng. Some well-capitalized investor will say =E2=80=9Cwow nickel prices are =
so high that the head of the LME says they=E2=80=99re crazy, I should short=
 some nickel,=E2=80=9D and the price comes back down through your sheer mor=
al authority.Or you could take more drastic action. If the prices are weird=
 because people are getting margin calls and being forced to buy (or sell),=
 you could loosen the margin rules, requiring less margin or giving people =
more time to pay. (In fact the LME  did that last week.) This is risky, but=
 it is a good idea if you are=C2=A0quite confident that the prices are wron=
g=C2=A0and will go back to normal.=C2=A0Or you could shut down trading for =
a bit. This has both of the previous effects: It sends a strong signal to t=
he market that prices are crazy, which will attract well-capitalized invest=
ors to take the other side and bring them back to normal, and it also gives=
 less-well-capitalized investors some time to line up more funding so they =
are not forced to trade at crazy prices. This is a very normal and often au=
tomated mechanism; plenty of exchanges have automatic trading pauses when p=
rices move very far very fast, on the theory that moves like that might be =
=E2=80=9Cwrong=E2=80=9D and so investors should take some time to think abo=
ut things. The LME did that in a more manual and=C2=A0dramatic way, suspend=
ing trading for a week.Or you could=C2=A0retroactively cancel the trades yo=
u think were crazy, which is a very drastic move and not really recommended=
; again the LME did that, and it got a lot of criticism for doing so. In ge=
neral I am  sympathetic to the critics =E2=80=94=C2=A0market prices are mar=
ket prices and you should not tear up trades between willing buyers and wil=
ling sellers because you don=E2=80=99t like the price or because it is bad =
for a few favored market participants =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I can see the LME=
=E2=80=99s side as well. It=E2=80=99s an exchange to set the price of nicke=
l, it wants to get the price right, and if the price is wildly wrong it wil=
l be tempted to fix it.=C2=A0The point is that if you are doing all of thes=
e quite drastic things it is because you are very confident that the price =
has gotten very wrong! You have a strong opinion that differs from the mark=
et price on the screen, and you are confident that your opinion is right, t=
he market is wrong, and you should override the market.=C2=A0If you have th=
at confidence, it seems strange to reopen trading a week later=C2=A0and say=
 =E2=80=9Cwell, this price is wrong, but we=E2=80=99re going to slowly ease=
 back to the correct price over the course of a week.=E2=80=9D Why keep tra=
ding at the wrong price? Why not fix the bad dynamics and then let the mark=
et find the correct price immediately?=C2=A0You=E2=80=99ve gone to a lot of=
 trouble because you decided that the price was wrong! Just make it right!
