At some point yesterday some compliance person at JPMorgan Chase & Co. got =
a question from an operations person. =E2=80=9CHey,=E2=80=9D said the opera=
tions person. =E2=80=9CYou know the account that we hold for the Russian go=
vernment? The one that is subject to harsh sanctions in the U.S. and much o=
f the rest of the world? They just asked us to make a $117 million payment =
out of that account. What should we do? By the way this is an interest paym=
ent on Russia=E2=80=99s dollar-denominated sovereign debt, and if we hold u=
p the money Russia will have defaulted on its foreign debt for the first ti=
me  since 1918. Let me know!=E2=80=9DAnd the compliance person sat down to =
read the text of the sanctions and conferred with some in-house lawyers hah=
ahaha no I=E2=80=99m kidding obviously a very senior person at JPMorgan cal=
led a very senior person at the U.S. Treasury and said =E2=80=9Ccan we pay =
this?=E2=80=9D and Treasury said =E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D and so JPMorgan did.=
 (Also probably this discussion happened well=C2=A0before yesterday=E2=80=
=99s payment request, which has been scheduled for some time.) The big bank=
s are in many ways quasi-regulatory bodies, extensions of the U.S. governme=
nt, particularly when it comes to sanctions. JPMorgan=C2=A0did not sit down=
 and make an independent business decision, or a legal decision, about whet=
her to pass along Russia=E2=80=99s interest payment. Treasury gets to decid=
e that sort of thing.The point is that  Treasury said yes:JPMorgan Chase & =
Co. has processed funds that were earmarked for interest payments due on do=
llar bonds issued by the Russian government and sent the money on to Citigr=
oup Inc., according to people familiar with the matter.JPMorgan was the cor=
respondent bank Russia used to send the payment to Citigroup, which is acti=
ng as payment agent on the bonds, the people said, asking not to be identif=
ied discussing a private matter. JPMorgan sent the money to Citigroup after=
 it sought and received the required approvals from U.S. authorities on Wed=
nesday, one of the people said. ...While European bondholders of Russia=E2=
=80=99s sovereign debt have received no sign of the funds, the move spurred=
 optimism that the bonds may be settled, sending prices higher across matur=
ities. The implied probability of a default by Russia within the year inche=
d lower to 57%, down from 59%, according to credit default swap pricing. La=
st week it was as high as 80%.=E2=80=9CThis seems to take a technical defau=
lt off the table for now,=E2=80=9D Kaan Nazli, a money manager at Neuberger=
 Berman in The Hague, Netherlands.=C2=A0It would actually be a bit strange =
if U.S. sanctions=C2=A0did=C2=A0prevent Russia from making payments in doll=
ars to foreign bondholders? In general U.S. sanctions prohibit any U.S. per=
son (including JPMorgan) from any dealings with Russia=E2=80=99s central ba=
nk or ministry of finance; =E2=80=9CThis action effectively immobilizes any=
 assets of the Central Bank of the Russian Federation held in the United St=
ates or by U.S. persons, wherever located.=E2=80=9D But, you know. The goal=
 is to prevent Russia from using its dollars to buy stuff, in order to put =
economic pressure on Russia. If Russia makes=C2=A0interest payments, on the=
 other hand:=09It will have fewer dollars, and=09It won=E2=80=99t get any n=
ew stuff.This is just a transfer of cash from Russia to (American, European=
, etc.) bondholders. Seems like something the U.S. would want to encourage.=
Meanwhile of course if Russia=C2=A0couldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0transfer the money=
 it would be in default. This would be bad for the (American, European, etc=
.) bondholders, who would not get their money. In abstract theory it would =
also be bad for Russia, because a country that is in default will have a to=
ugh time borrowing in international debt markets. But of course=C2=A0the sa=
nctions did that already, and Russia can=E2=80=99t really borrow any more d=
ollars from its international bondholders, so defaulting on the debt would =
not change its position much. A default would be bad for bondholders and no=
t particularly bad for Russia. So there is no real reason for the U.S. Trea=
sury to force a default. So it okayed the payment.On the other hand I am no=
t entirely sure why Russia=C2=A0made=C2=A0the payment; Russia has imposed c=
apital controls to preserve dollars, and earlier this month Vladimir Putin =
 signed a decree saying that=C2=A0=E2=80=9CRussia and Russian companies wil=
l be allowed to pay foreign creditors in rubles on securities including tho=
se denominated in other currencies.=E2=80=9D Given its limited stock of dol=
lars and its antagonism to Western investors, and the fact that it is shut =
out of capital markets anyway, it is not at all clear why it would want to =
pay those dollars to those investors. But apparently it does, and the U.S. =
will let it.
