I am not personally an expert meme-stock trader or anything, but I gather t=
hat the cool way to trade meme stocks is with short-dated out-of-the-money =
call options. (Nothing in this column is ever investing advice, but this is=
 even less investing advice than usual.)=C2=A0Ideally each week you would b=
uy call options expiring that Friday with a strike price of, you know, 200%=
 or so of the current stock price. The options are very cheap, and if the s=
tock quadruples in three days you make a ton of money.There are three big a=
dvantages to this trade, versus just buying the stock:=09High leverage: You=
 spend a small amount for these very-likely-to-be-worthless options, and yo=
u get exposure to a lot of stock. If the stock really does go to the moon, =
you make a lot of money from a small outlay.=09=E2=80=9CGamma squeeze=E2=80=
=9D: In theory, your buying causes options market makers to=C2=A0buy more s=
tock, pushing the stock up and making this a self-fulfilling prophecy. Don=
=E2=80=99t get=C2=A0too=C2=A0excited about this effect, but it may have bee=
n part of the story of why GameStop Corp. went up so much last January: Lot=
s of retail investors were buying out-of-the-money options, and dealers wer=
e hedging by buying the stock.=09YOLO: Your goal in buying meme stocks is n=
ot necessarily to make the highest possible risk-adjusted return but rather=
 to have fun gambling and impress your online friends with how reckless and=
 all-in you are. Putting all your money into a trade that will lose everyth=
ing unless the stock doubles in three days is reckless and all-in and, for =
a certain temperament, maybe fun?Meanwhile, this is also not investment adv=
ice, or legal advice, but one thing that I=C2=A0say a lot around here is th=
at if you have inside information about an upcoming merger announcement, yo=
u should=C2=A0especially=C2=A0not buy short-dated out-of-the-money call opt=
ions on the merger target. (I call this the Second Law of Insider Trading.)=
 That=E2=80=99s how they catch you!=C2=A0Regulators do look at unusual trad=
ing before merger announcements, and particularly unusual trading in instru=
ments that will only pay out if the stock moves dramatically in a short tim=
e. That just looks like a precise bet on a merger announcement, which is su=
spicious.Now these things go together? Last week, small-cap gold mining com=
pany Hycroft Mining Holding Corp.  became a meme stock: =E2=80=9CReddit inv=
estors started talking about Hycroft and drove its stock up to a high of $1=
.88 on March 11, the stock=E2=80=99s highest price since August.=E2=80=9D H=
ycroft has options expiring this Friday, March 18, and open interest in the=
 $2.50 call option shot up from 20 contracts on March 7 to 15,806 contracts=
 on March 14. As Hycroft=C2=A0became a meme, people wanted to buy a lot of =
short-dated out-of-the-money call options, because that=E2=80=99s the cool =
way to trade meme stocks.On March 15, Hycroft announced that it was getting=
 an equity investment from AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc., the king of the=
 meme stocks. This caused Hycroft=E2=80=99s stock to go up by 9% (though to=
 below the $1.88 that it hit last week), and was, I think it is fair to say=
, both mergers-and-acquisitions news and also meme news. If you bought thos=
e call options right before the AMC deal, doesn=E2=80=99t that look a littl=
e suspicious?Well, no, not really, since Hycroft=E2=80=99s stock has since =
fallen (presumably because it=E2=80=99s doing a huge  at-the-market stock o=
ffering to sell into all of the meme-y demand), and the $2.50 Friday=C2=A0o=
ptions have fallen even further and seem likely to expire worthless (not in=
vesting advice!). Still. The genesis of this deal seems to have been:=09Hyc=
roft became a meme.=09Hycroft called AMC for advice on how it could get mon=
ey from being a meme.=09AMC was like =E2=80=9Ctell you what, we=E2=80=99ll =
give you some money, we=E2=80=99ll meme you even more, and we=E2=80=99ll bo=
th make money out of the memes.=E2=80=9DAnd you could imagine this happenin=
g again.  I wrote: =E2=80=9CAMC is an investment bank, or really a merchant=
 bank that helps small companies do meme-driven at-the-market offerings and=
 takes equity for its fee.=E2=80=9D Next time AMC sees a company become a m=
eme and announces a deal, there will probably once again be a lot of people=
 who bought short-dated out-of-the-money call options on the company just b=
efore the deal is announced. Were they insider trading, or were they YOLOin=
g a meme?
