10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note: </strong><em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><table class=3D"header" =
width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Nickel</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a silly=C2=A0but not entirely =
inaccurate description of the nickel market right now:</p><ol style=3D"list=
-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Nickel is worth, let=E2=80=99s say, somewhere between =
$30,000 and $35,000 per ton.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Every=
one kind of knows that.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">For reason=
s of historical accident and market technicals, the price of nickel on the =
London Metal Exchange, the main venue for nickel trading, was set at $48,07=
8 per ton at the start of trading yesterday morning, about 40% above the re=
al price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The LME declared that th=
e price could drop by only 5% per day (since expanded to 8% per day) until =
it reached the real price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So that=
=E2=80=99s happening now: It fell 5% yesterday, fell 8% today, will fall 8%=
 tomorrow, etc., until it hits the real price sometime around next Tuesday.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The price is preordained so there=
 is not much to do: Each day the LME opens for trading, promptly falls 8% t=
o reach the limit,=C2=A0and then closes again.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">Nor is there much volume because, you know, if the real price =
of nickel is $35,000, why are you paying $42,000?</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">But there=E2=80=99s <em>some</em> volume, and the only real=
 question is who gets to the front of the line to sell nickel at today=E2=
=80=99s inflated price before the market shuts and you have to wait until t=
omorrow for it to fall some more.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I m=
ean? I am kidding? But only a little? It is not=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>t=
he case that nickel is definitely worth $30,000 to $35,000 a ton, or that e=
veryone knows that, or that the price will automatically keep dropping 8% a=
 day. (This is not investment advice!) But it kind of looks like that? It i=
s not a great look?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let me explain a bit mo=
re.=C2=A0At the beginning of March, nickel was trading at about $25,000 a t=
on. Since then nickel has become more valuable as Russia=E2=80=99s invasion=
 of Ukraine has put pressure on nickel supplies. The fundamental value has =
gone up, to perhaps $30,000 or $35,000 a ton, somewhere=C2=A0in that ballpa=
rk, the exact number doesn=E2=80=99t matter.[1] However, due to a short squ=
eeze on the London Metal Exchange, nickel futures shot up last week, and th=
e price <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27061747.2=
58600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMTQva=
W5zaWRlLW5pY2tlbC1zLXNob3J0LXNxdWVlemUtaG93LXByaWNlLXN1cmdlcy1oYWx0ZWQtbG1l=
LXRyYWRpbmc_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMxNzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb73faf99" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> climbed above $100,000 per t=
on</a> early in the morning of Tuesday, March 8.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">In general the point of a futures market is to discover the cor=
rect price for a commodity. But in the case of LME nickel last week, everyo=
ne =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, at least, everyone running the LME =E2=80=94=C2=A0sor=
t of looked around and said =E2=80=9Cwell this is not the correct price of =
nickel now is it.=E2=80=9D (The chief executive officer of the LME <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27061747.258600/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMTQvaW5zaWRlLW5pY2tl=
bC1zLXNob3J0LXNxdWVlemUtaG93LXByaWNlLXN1cmdlcy1oYWx0ZWQtbG1lLXRyYWRpbmc_Y21=
waWQ9QkJEMDMxNzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3=
NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cCb73faf99" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">said that</a>=C2=A0the trading prices =E2=80=
=9Cwere becoming disconnected from, I believe, physical reality.=E2=80=9D) =
The LME, and many big metals traders, decided that the correct price of nic=
kel was not $100,000. So the LME canceled last Tuesday=E2=80=99s trades =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0a drastic step that took away the profits and losses many trade=
rs had made on nickel that morning =E2=80=94=C2=A0and rolled the price back=
 to $48,078, where nickel had closed last Monday.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Then the LME closed for a week to give people time to resolve the we=
ird short-squeeze dynamics that had driven up the price. In particular, the=
re is one big nickel producer, Tsingshan Holding Group Co., run by nickel t=
ycoon Xiang Guangda, that was short a lot=C2=A0of nickel contracts on the L=
ME and got big margin calls last week and did not put up more money. Some o=
f its brokers bought back nickel contracts rather than posting more margin,=
 which drove the price up more, which led to more margin calls, more forced=
 selling, etc. Because all of this was somewhat silly =E2=80=94=C2=A0Tsings=
han is probably good for the money, since it is a nickel producer and the p=
rice of nickel is going up! =E2=80=94=C2=A0the way to fix it was to shut do=
wn the market for a while to let Tsingshan and others borrow enough money (=
against their valuable nickel) to pay margin calls without having to buy ba=
ck their futures contracts. And that=E2=80=99s what happened, and they line=
d up financing, and when the market reopened yesterday the short squeeze wa=
s greatly alleviated. Nobody was forced to buy nickel at prices that they t=
hought were absurd, so they were all free to buy or sell nickel at the corr=
ect price.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Except, uh, no they weren=E2=80=
=99t, because the LME imposed price limits: The price of nickel could only =
rise or fall 5% yesterday, from last Monday=E2=80=99s closing price of $48,=
078, when the short squeeze had already started and =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27061747.258600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMTQvaW5zaWRlLW5pY2tlbC1zLXN=
ob3J0LXNxdWVlemUtaG93LXByaWNlLXN1cmdlcy1oYWx0ZWQtbG1lLXRyYWRpbmc_Y21waWQ9Qk=
JEMDMxNzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0Z=
XImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cDb73faf99" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> the market had started to unravel</a>.=E2=80=9D It=
 was not=C2=A0<em>completely=C2=A0</em>certain that the price would fall 5%=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0when Bloomberg <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/27061747.258600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMTUvbGltaXQtdXAtb3ItbGltaXQtZG93bi1uaWNrZWwtdHJhZGVycy1hc=
mUtYnJhY2luZy1mb3Itd2lsZC1yaWRlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMTcyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9t=
ZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDMxNyZ1dG1fY2F=
tcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1192398e" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> surveye=
d 16 analysts and traders</a> before the reopening, 13 said that it would f=
all 5%, but one said it would <em>rise</em> 5%, =E2=80=9Cwhile the other tw=
o said either scenario is possible=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it was the m=
ost obvious outcome. Everyone seemed to think that the prices last week =E2=
=80=9Cwere becoming disconnected from physical reality,=E2=80=9D and the LM=
E had done the necessary things to get the price back in line with physical=
 reality, so it stood to reason that the price would fall back to physical =
reality. But because the LME put the brakes on how fast it could fall =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0from last week=E2=80=99s unreal price! =E2=80=94=C2=A0it couldn=
=E2=80=99t do that all at once.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so the =
price immediately fell 5% yesterday, on very light volume (why sell at the =
wrong price?), and closed at $45,590.[2] To speed things along a little bit=
, the LME <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27061747=
.258600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubG1lLmNvbS9hcGkvc2l0ZWNvcmUvTWVtYmVyTm90aWNlc1NlYXJ=
jaEFwaS9Eb3dubG9hZD9pZD02ZTYyYTI0Yi1mOTUwLTQ1MjQtYmJhMS0yMGQ4ZmY5M2FkN2I/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB85a7e6bd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">then announced</a> that=C2=A0<em>t=
oday=C2=A0</em>the price can fall (or rise?) by up to 8%. So it opened toda=
y, fell 8% to $41,945, and promptly stopped trading.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">I mean, that is a rough intuitive description of what happe=
ned today; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2706174=
7.258600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMT=
cvbG1lLW5pY2tlbC10cmFkZXJzLWF3YWtlLXRvLWZyZXNoLW1heWhlbS1hcy1yZW9wZW5pbmctZ=
GVsYXllZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzE3MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9z=
b3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAzMTcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9d7d4013" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here=E2=80=99s what actually h=
appened</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The start of the s=
econd day of trading after a week-long suspension was delayed to 8:45 a.m. =
after a series of problems hit the LME=E2=80=99s electronic system. First, =
brokers found that orders to sell at the lower-limit of 8% below Wednesday=
=E2=80=99s closing price were being rejected, after the LME expanded the tr=
ading band the previous day.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then three tra=
des did appear to go through at that price -- but four minutes before the m=
arket had been due to open. Finally, the LME informed brokers that trading =
wouldn=E2=80=99t restart until 8:45 a.m. and canceled the three earlier tra=
des. When the market finally opened, futures dropped by the daily limit of =
8% to $41,945 a ton. But only two trades had taken place by 9:00 a.m.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The chaotic start to the session piles embarrass=
ment on the LME as it seeks to restore order to the market that sets global=
 prices for one of the world=E2=80=99s most important metals. The crisis in=
 nickel has sparked furious criticism of the exchange for its handling of t=
he situation, from metals markets veterans as well as generalist investors,=
 and several have said they will stop trading on the market.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CCredibility is very quickly slipping through the=
ir fingers,=E2=80=9D Keith Wildie, head of trading at Romco Metals, said by=
 phone from London. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s eroding very rapidly.=E2=80=9D</p=
></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Good times, good times.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, as we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/27061747.258600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9v=
