<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Energy</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The nickel market, as I hope I have co=
nveyed, is weird. But at a high level it is not <em>that</em> weird. Nickel=
 was bopping along at some normal price. Nickel producers and users and tra=
ders and speculators were trading nickel futures to hedge their price risk =
or to bet on price moves. They all had to post margin to secure their oblig=
ations under the futures contracts,=C2=A0and as prices moved one side had t=
o post more margin (and the other got some margin back). The traders and th=
eir brokers and the exchange all had models about how much prices typically=
 moved, and those models affected their risk management decisions: how much=
 margin to demand, how many futures to sell to a client, how much cash to h=
ave on hand to meet margin calls, etc.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And =
then a big surprising geopolitical event =E2=80=94=C2=A0Russia=E2=80=99s in=
vasion of Ukraine =E2=80=94=C2=A0pushed up the price of nickel more and fas=
ter than people expected. Traders were not ready for it; they did not have =
the cash on hand to meet margin calls, so they were forced to buy back cont=
racts and the price went up in a vicious cycle that left the price of nicke=
l futures =E2=80=9Cdisconnected from physical reality.=E2=80=9D And the mar=
ket broke in various ways that we discussed above.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The particular ways in which it broke are probably specific to the =
nickel market, but the general dynamic of =E2=80=9Cgeopolitical event leads=
 to spiking commodity price leads to margin calls leads to market dislocati=
on=E2=80=9D could apply to lots of things. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/27061747.258600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbn=
QvNmNkYzQ4NTktZGI4Yy00MTM3LTg0MzYtMmExMGNiNTBmNTc5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B40675101" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">For instance here=E2=80=99s gas and power</a>:</p><block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Europe=E2=80=99s largest energy traders =
have called on governments and central banks to provide =E2=80=9Cemergency=
=E2=80=9D assistance to avert a cash crunch as sharp price moves triggered =
by the Ukraine crisis strain commodity markets.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">In a letter seen by the Financial Times, the European Federation of En=
ergy Traders =E2=80=94 a trade body that counts BP, Shell and commodity tra=
ders Vitol and Trafigura as members =E2=80=94 said the industry needed =E2=
=80=9Ctime-limited emergency liquidity support to ensure that wholesale gas=
 and power markets continued to function=E2=80=9D. ...</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSince the end of February 2022, an already challenging=
 situation has worsened and more [European] energy participants are in [a] =
position where their ability to source additional liquidity is severely red=
uced or, in some cases, exhausted,=E2=80=9D EFET said in its letter, dated =
March 8 and sent to market participants and regulators.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">It was =E2=80=9Cnot infeasible to foresee=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=
=E2=80=89. generally sound and healthy energy companies=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=
=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89unable to access cash=E2=80=9D, the letter warned. Peopl=
e familiar with the matter said EFET members had raised the issue with cent=
ral banks. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Futures linked to TTF,=
 Europe=E2=80=99s wholesale gas price, surged almost 200 per cent over four=
 days earlier this month. In some cases, variation, or mark-to-market margi=
n, in the gas market have increased 10 times from one day to another.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">EFET wants state entities such as the European I=
nvestment Bank or central banks, such as the European Central Bank or the B=
ank of England, to provide support through lenders, to soften the impact of=
 margin calls.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe overriding obje=
ctive is to keep an orderly market for futures and other derivative energy =
contracts open,=E2=80=9D said Peter Styles, executive vice-chair of the EFE=
T board, in an interview. =E2=80=9CGas producers, European gas importers =
=E2=80=8Band power suppliers must retain the opportunity to hedge their pos=
itions.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, broadl=
y speaking, you=E2=80=99d expect rising energy prices to be good for energy=
 companies, and rising volatility to be good for energy traders, though the=
re are caveats to that.[3] But just as in nickel the point is that, when yo=
ur required margin goes up 1,000% overnight, you have an immediate cash nee=
d that you might not be able to meet=C2=A0by saying =E2=80=9Cwell but all o=
ur oil in the ground has also become=C2=A0more valuable.=E2=80=9D In some e=
conomic sense that=E2=80=99s correct, but you need the money=C2=A0<em>today=
</em>, and the oil is in the ground.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so=
 the risk is that you won=E2=80=99t be able to meet margin calls, that you =
might be forced to buy back futures and push the price up even higher, that=
 this will become a vicious cycle, that the futures price will become disco=
nnected from economic fundamentals, that some market participants with good=
 underlying businesses will go bankrupt, that the market will stop working.=
 The risk is that the system was too finely tuned to relatively benign cond=
itions, and that a geopolitical shock that ought to be good for energy comp=
anies might nonetheless blow them up.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In th=
e nickel section we discussed various ways of handling this: Soften margin =
requirements (risky!), shut down trading (hard to do with gas and power mar=
kets!), talk down the price, etc. But I neglected to mention a great one, w=
hich is: Ask central banks to step in and pay your margin requirements for =
you. The major central banks essentially cannot run out of money, so this s=
olves the problem completely. And if the diagnosis is correct =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0that the economic fundamentals are fine, but weird technical margin-call=
 issues might blow up otherwise healthy companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the r=
isk to the central banks is minimal; they will just fix the market and get =
their money bank.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously this is, uh, po=
litically weird? Like, probably this never occurred to anyone in the nickel=
 market, because:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 4=
0px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Nickel, for all =
of its industrial importance, is not generally a headline-grabbing financia=
l product, and nickel traders do not have central banks on speed dial, and<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The main person who needs a bailou=
t is a Chinese nickel tycoon who =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/27061747.258600/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQ=
vMmNiNzMxMzgtMjRhZS00ZTEwLWE4ZmQtNTU1OGM3MTU1NDYx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
a6706e08" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">loves to punt</a>,=E2=80=9D and there is absolutely no wa=
y on earth that the Fed was going to backstop his margin requirements.</li>=
</ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But energy prices are very politically se=
nsitive, big commodity traders are feeling the pain broadly,=C2=A0and I sup=
pose you could imagine this appeal working?=C2=A0Here is my Bloomberg Opini=
